Introduction¶

In this report, I chose to analyze the TMDb (The Movie Database) dataset. The dataset contains information on movies from the 1960s through 2015, and includes financial information, ratings, release dates, actors, studios, and more.

In my first question, I am going to look at what makes a movie a success or a failure, and dig deeper into why that might be.

In my second question, I am going to look at what some of the properties are of high revenue movies.

Checking for Null Values¶

Here, I have created a more informative output, showing total nulls per column and calculating the percent. I have temporarily restricted the decimal points to two, and limited the results to only those columns which contain nulls.

In [7]:
# Checking for Null Values
total = df.isnull().sum().sort_values(ascending=False)
percent = ((df.isnull().sum()/df.isnull().count())*100).sort_values(ascending=False)
missing = pd.concat([total, percent], axis=1, keys=['Total', 'Percent'])
pd.set_option('precision', 2)

I had never heard of a movie with a budget that high, nor had I ever heard of the movie. I went to The Movie DB's website where this data was pulled from and looked up the movie and found that the budget was actually $42,000,000. I would have assumed that this data was pulled from their database, and that the same database would be queried for the display on their website. Apparently, that is not the case and it seems there may be some human error introduced into the dataset.

Since I can confirm that the dataset is wrong for that movie, I am going to change the value for that column to be the value that is stated on the website.

The reason I am explaining this here is because in that section, I went through about 10 steps before getting to the point of seeing this error, and if I fixed it in place I would have to redo those 10 steps, making this report longer and more confusing. Thus, I am changing it in the cleanup section and explaining the change now, and as a result I will get accurate results the first time.

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

Question 1: What effect does budget and revenue have on the success of a movie?¶

Explanation¶

Asking this question can bring about a lot of debate on what qualifies as a success. It is generally accepted that in order for a movie to be considered successful, it has to earn back at least twice it's budget. This is to account for not only the cost of making the film, but also the massive marketing campaign that frequently accompanies these films, which isn't included in the budget and can sometimes even exceed the cost of production. This is not a firm line that must be met, but that is the guideline I am going to use for this report.

Below are two links to web pages that discuss this:

https://io9.gizmodo.com/5747305/how-much-money-does-a-movie-need-to-make-to-be-profitable

https://www.quora.com/What-are-the-criteria-for-a-movie-hit-super-hit-blockbuster-and-flop see first 2 answers

The reason this question is important is because determining the success can indicate whether a studio will make a sequel or something similar in the future. Even if the net exceeds the budget, if the movie can't make up for the cost of promoting it, then the chances they will make another goes down.

I realize that this is a broad question that could go in many different directions. For this project, I am going to focus on the financial aspect.

Dealing with Zeros¶

This question deals with the financial columns of the dataset, so the data needs to be altered to deal with all the zeros that are in the budget and revenue columns. If I leave the zeros in, it will result in false analysis. I tested this beforehand, and having a zero makes a movie a failure by default, which skews the data heavily on the failure side. I don't know if the zeros mean they didn't make any money or if they simply don't have the data, but since there so many zeros in the budget column, I lean towards them not having the info.

To deal with this, these rows will need to be removed, which will significanly reduce the dataset. However, there will still be close to 4000 rows of data to work with. If we assume that the average movie is 2 hours long, and all you did was watch movies 24 hours a day, it would take over 10 months to get through them all! That is plenty of movies to work with.

If I was presented with a dataset like this on the job, I would take additional steps to find out if I could get the missing data, and if not, why not. In this case, I can only work with what I have currently.

Create a Column 'Profit'¶

I am creating a column called profit where I take revenue - (budget * 2) to account for the marketing campaign as discussed in the question explanation. If the value in the profit column is greater than zero, it means the movie made at least double its budget or higher. Less than zero means it did not double its budget.

Creating a Column Called 'Success'¶

Here I am creating a new column called success that will populate with 'Success' if the profit is greater than zero, and 'Failure' if less than zero. Anything above zero indicates the movie earned back twice it's budget to account for the marketing campaign; less than zero they possibly still made more than the budget, but did not meet the criteria of success as discussed in the question explanation.

Summary of Success vs Failure¶

Overall, the movies in this dataset are considered successes more than failures, but it's close at 2008 to 1797. The results show a ratio of approximately 53:47. There were 748 movies that had a positive net value, but did not double their budget in revenue, which resulted in those movies being considered failures along with all the movies that had negative net values.

Heatmap¶

A heatmap provides the same statistics as a .corr but the addition of color coding makes it much easier to see correlations.

In [73]:
# Create heatmap of dfnz
plt.figure(figsize = (15,8))

plt.xticks(rotation=-45);

Heatmap Observations¶

The heatmap shows that budget and revenue have a correlation of 0.696, which is on the cusp between moderate and strong correlation. Having the actual number is beneficial, because the scatterplot above can be open to interpretation as to whether or not the correlation is moderate or strong.

Considering Failures¶

I have been focused on budget and revenue, but recall that the success vs failure rates were pretty close to each other. What I've just shown is that there is somewhat of a correlation between budget and revenue, but the failure rate would indicate there are definitely some exceptions.

Below I am looking at net values that are negative, i.e, a loss. Specifically, any movie that has a net value of negative $10 million or more. Net has to be used because by definition you can't have negative profit.

In [75]:

12.562417871222076

There are 478 movies that lost $10 million dollars or more. That turns out to be about 12.5% of the 3805 movies in this dataframe that lost a significant amount of money.

If you apply 12.5% failures to the full 9770 of the original dataset, that would be over 1200 movies that lost $10 million or more.

Genres¶

Lastly, I want to explore genres and how they relate to revenue. I will continue to use the toprev dataframe for this.

Splitting the Genres Column¶

The genres column is mostly populated with more than one genre per movie, separated by a pipe. Additionally, each movie can have a different number of genres. This makes it difficult to deal with. The only way to do it is to drop the genres column, split it, and join the results back. However, this effectively creates duplicate rows of the same movie, where all the data is the same except the genre. So a movie where the genres column is Action|Adventure|Comedy now has 3 rows, one for each of those 3 genres. This also artificially inflates the size of the dataframe.

In [96]:
# Splitting out genres and joining them back in
toprev_genres = toprev.drop('genres', axis=1).join(toprev['genres'].str.split('|', expand=True).stack().reset_index(level=1, drop=True).rename('genre'))

Conclusions¶

Question 1¶

In question 1, I explored the financial aspect of what makes a movie successful or a failure. Specifically, the criteria for success was that the movie at a minimum doubled its budget in revenue. This was calculated in a new variable labeled as profit.

The results showed there were 2,008 successes and 1,797 failures, which is approximately a 53:47 success/failure rate. I arrived at this result after using less than half the original dataset because so many entries did not have revenue or budget data, and often both were missing.

I followed that up by analyzing budget and revenue to see if there was any correlation between the variables. I found a moderate to strong correlation at 0.696. This was further confirmed by looking at movies with large budgets (over $50 million) that had significant net losses. Approximately 12.5% of movies lost 10 million dollars or more, which demonstrates that while there is a correlation with budget and revenue, a large budget does not necessarily mean success.

It's important to keep in mind the criteria that was set for what is considered a success; there were 748 movies that still made money, just not double their budgets, which labeled them as failures. Since this is not a firm rule, movie studios are not bound by it, and could still decide to make sequels. I do not have marketing data for any movie, so it is entirely possible that a movie didn't have a huge marketing cost, and even though it didn't double its budget, it still made enough money for the studio to take a chance on making a sequel.

Question 2¶

In question 2, I looked at what properties movies with high revenues (over $50 million) might have. I looked at three variables: runtime, vote count, and genres.

In regards to runtime, I found that movies with high revenues had an average runtime of 113 minutes, and the bulk fell into a range of between 98 and 124 minutes. This however, does not have a strong correlation to revenue, as when I plotted runtime and revenue the trend line was low, and the heatmap showed a very low correlation. However, that being said, logically speaking, I still think runtime can have an effect on a movie's revenue. For instance, a 3-hour movie likely turns some people off from seeing it in the theater because they don't want to sit through a movie that long. This is obviously the exception and not the rule, which is likely one reason the correlation is so low, but it is a consideration that studios likely take into account.

When looking at vote count, there seemed to be a fairly strong trend when I plotted it against revenue. I was initially concerned that the dataset skewing heavily toward recent movies in shear count was throwing off the analysis. I looked more closely at the number of movies and vote counts before and after the year 2000, and the trend remained fairly constant, so that was not an issue. Looking back at the heatmap, vote count had a moderately strong correlation to revenue at 0.716. In fact, it was the strongest correlation to revenue of all possible variables (net and profit are not useable to predict revenue).

The caveat to using vote count as a predictor to revenue is that it comes after the movie is released. So, it could be used as a predictor after the initial weekend run of the movie looking towards the long term success of the box office run. It could also be used as a predictor to how much people enjoyed the movie, and would want to see a sequel. For example, a movie might get a high amount of attendance through marketing and name recognition, but viewers left disappointed. Vote count could provide the studio with an idea of how well the movie was received, rather than simply relying on revenue alone. Some movies actually do better with streaming/Blu ray sales than they did in the box office.

With genres, I found that movies with high revenues had genres of drama, comedy, action, thriller, and adventure as the top 5, both in terms of occurrences and revenue, though in differing orders. However, those five had close to double the amount or more occurrences than the other genres. I believe that indicates that those top 5 cover are used too liberally, and that the others not on the top 5 are likely better descriptors of the type of movie it is. Additionally, the majority of movies in the dataset had more than 1 genre attached to it. Between the overuse of the top 5 genre labels, and multiple genres per movie, it is difficult to use genre as a predictor. A more targeted use of genre would likely yield better results.
